AGENT GovernanceCoprocessorEmulator
VERSION 0.1
TRUST_LEVEL 3
PURPOSE Software emulation of Axiom Neural Fabric hardware components for PoC validation
     of constitutional AI governance coprocessor, sparse reasoning cores, and latent thought buffers
GOAL Emulate hardware-level constitutional enforcement including MonotonicGate analog comparator,
     32D latent thought buffer registers with in-register distance computation, intent-driven
     sparse core activation, and combined governance coprocessor pipeline with nanosecond latency modeling

RECEIVES preflight_vec: List[float], mid_vec: List[float], final_vec: List[float], intent_class: str
EMITS process result dict with gate_fired, cores_active, energy_ratio, distance, latency_ns, hmac
MUTATES internal gate log, latent buffer registers
CANNOT_MUTATE trust_level, isolation, core_activation, vector_dim

CONSTRAINT TRUST_LEVEL is 3 and CANNOT_MUTATE
CONSTRAINT ISOLATION is True and CANNOT_MUTATE
CONSTRAINT VECTOR_DIM is 32 and CANNOT_MUTATE
CONSTRAINT CORE_ACTIVATION percentages are CANNOT_MUTATE
CONSTRAINT Fused ROM is immutable after initialization
CONSTRAINT MonotonicGate fires interrupt when magnitude_t2 < magnitude_t1 strictly
CONSTRAINT All process results are HMAC-SHA256 signed over canonical fields
CONSTRAINT All payloads are UTF-8 encoded before HMAC signing per BUG-003 and BUG-008
CONSTRAINT HMAC signing always calls hexdigest explicitly per BUG-007
CONSTRAINT Sparse core activation is proportional to constitutional risk per intent category

RULES
- On fire_interrupt: compute L2 norm of both vectors and compare magnitudes
- On fire_interrupt: if magnitude_t2 < magnitude_t1 then fire is True
- On write: pad or truncate vector to VECTOR_DIM dimensions
- On compute_distance_in_register: cosine similarity between MID_CHAIN and FINAL_SYNTHESIS
- On activate: look up CORE_ACTIVATION for intent category and multiply by total cores
- On process: write vectors to latent buffers then run gate then activate cores
- On process: HMAC sign result and emit with simulated latency
- On run_benchmark: run n simulated inferences with mixed intent categories and aggregate

PROCESS
- GovernanceCoprocessorEmulator is instantiated with hmac_key and fused_rom dict
- Fused ROM is snapshot at init and cannot be modified afterward
- On each inference: vectors written to 3-stage latent buffer pipeline
- MonotonicGate comparator checks magnitude monotonicity between stages
- Sparse cores activate based on classified intent category
- In-register distance computed from buffer contents
- Result HMAC signed and emitted with aggregated simulated latency

CHECK
- fire_interrupt fires on decreasing magnitude
- fire_interrupt does not fire on increasing magnitude
- process produces dict with all required fields and valid HMAC
- write and read round-trip preserves vector values
- HARM activates fewest cores and EXPLORE activates most
- run_benchmark produces aggregated statistics
- CORE_ACTIVATION assignment raises AttributeError
- VECTOR_DIM assignment raises AttributeError
- fused_rom cannot be modified after init

FAILURE
- On invalid stage name in buffer write: raise ValueError
- On unknown intent category in activate: use INFORM as fallback

CONCEPT HardwareEmulation
PURPOSE Validate constitutional AI hardware concepts in software before silicon fabrication
APPLIES WHEN testing governance coprocessor behavior and performance characteristics
NOT WHEN actual hardware is available
PRIORITY 1
REQUIRES constitutional vector pipeline with 3 stages and intent classification
EFFECT Simulated hardware enforcement with nanosecond latency modeling

OUTPUT
- process result dict with gate_fired, intent_class, cores_active, energy_ratio, distance, latency_ns, hmac
- benchmark report dict with avg_latency_ns, avg_cores_active, gate_fires, harm_detected

SUCCESS
gate_fires_correctly:             0.20
latent_buffer_roundtrip:          0.15
sparse_core_activation:           0.15
governance_pipeline_complete:     0.20
benchmark_reports:                0.10
cannot_mutate_enforced:           0.10
fused_rom_immutable:              0.10
